318  // SiteData aka building data
319  extern Real64 LowHConvLimit; // Lowest allowed convection coefficient for detailed model
320  // before reverting to the simple model. This avoids a
321  // divide by zero elsewhere. Not based on any physical
322  // reasoning, just the number that was picked. It corresponds
323  // to a delta T for a vertical surface of 0.000444C.
324  // REAL(r64), PARAMETER :: LowHConvLimit = 1.0 !W/m2-K Lowest allowed natural convection coefficient
325  // ! A lower limit is needed to avoid numerical problems
326  // ! Natural convection correlations are a function of temperature difference,
327  // ! there are many times when those temp differences pass through zero leading to non-physical results
328  // ! Value of 1.0 chosen here is somewhat arbitrary, but based on the following reasons:
329  // ! 1) Low values of HconvIn indicate a layer of high thermal resistance, however
330  // ! the R-value of a convection film layer should be relatively low (compared to building surfaces)
331  // ! 2) The value of 1.0 corresponds to the thermal resistance of 0.05 m of batt insulation
332  // ! 3) Limit on the order of 1.0 is suggested by the abrupt changes in an inverse relationship
333  // ! 4) A conduction-only analysis can model a limit by considering the thermal performance of
334  // ! boundary layer to be pure conduction (with no movement to enhance heat transfer);
335  // ! Taking the still gas thermal conductivity for air at 0.0267 W/m-K (at 300K), then
336  // ! this limit of 1.0 corresponds to a completely still layer of air that is around 0.025 m thick
337  // ! 5) The previous limit of 0.1 (before ver. 3.1) caused loads initialization problems in test files
338  extern Real64 HighHConvLimit; // upper limit for HConv, mostly used for user input limits in practice. !W/m2-K
339  extern Real64 MaxAllowedDelTempCondFD; // Convergence criteria for inside surface temperatures for CondFD
340

855  struct ConstructionData
856  {
857  // Members
858  std::string Name; // Name of construction
859  int TotLayers; // Total number of layers for the construction; for windows
860  // this is the total of the glass, gas and shade layers
861  int TotSolidLayers; // Total number of solid (glass or shade) layers (windows only)
862  int TotGlassLayers; // Total number of glass layers (windows only)
863  Array1D_int LayerPoint; // Pointer array which refers back to
864  // the Material structure; LayerPoint(i)=j->Material(j)%Name,etc
865  bool IsUsed; // Marked true when the construction is used
866  bool IsUsedCTF; // Mark true when the construction is used for a surface with CTF calculations
867  Real64 InsideAbsorpVis; // Inside Layer visible absorptance of an opaque surface; not used for windows.
868  Real64 OutsideAbsorpVis; // Outside Layer visible absorptance of an opaque surface; not used for windows.
869  Real64 InsideAbsorpSolar; // Inside Layer solar absorptance of an opaque surface; not used for windows.
870  Real64 OutsideAbsorpSolar; // Outside Layer solar absorptance of an opaque surface; not used for windows.
871  Real64 InsideAbsorpThermal; // Inside Layer Thermal absorptance for opaque surfaces or windows;
872  // for windows, applies to innermost glass layer
873  Real64 OutsideAbsorpThermal; // Outside Layer Thermal absorptance
874  int OutsideRoughness; // Outside Surface roughness index (6=very smooth, 5=smooth,
875  // 4=medium smooth, 3=medium rough, 2=rough, 1=very rough)
876  int DayltPropPtr; // Pointer to Daylight Construction Properties
877  int W5FrameDivider; // FrameDivider number for window construction from Window5 data file;
878  // zero is construction not from Window5 file or Window5 construction has no frame.
879  // Conductive properties for the construction
880  Array1D<Real64> CTFCross; // Cross or Y terms of the CTF equation
881  Array1D<Real64> CTFFlux; // Flux history terms of the CTF equation
882  Array1D<Real64> CTFInside; // Inside or Z terms of the CTF equation
883  Array1D<Real64> CTFOutside; // Outside or X terms of the CTF equation
884  Array1D<Real64> CTFSourceIn; // Heat source/sink inside terms of CTF equation
885  Array1D<Real64> CTFSourceOut; // Heat source/sink outside terms of CTF equation
886  Real64 CTFTimeStep; // Time increment for stable simulation of construct (could be greater than TimeStep)
887  // The next three series of terms are used to calculate the temperature at the location of a source/sink
888  // in the QTF formulation. This calculation is necessary to allow the proper simulation of a
889  // radiant system.
890  Array1D<Real64> CTFTSourceOut; // Outside terms of the CTF equation for interior temp
891  // calc@source location
892  Array1D<Real64> CTFTSourceIn; // Inside terms of the CTF equation for interior temp
893  // calc@source location
894  Array1D<Real64> CTFTSourceQ; // Source/sink terms of the CTF equation for interior temp
895  // calc@source location
896  // The next three series of terms are used to calculate the temperature at a location specified by the user.
897  // This location must be between two layers and is intended to allow the user to evaluate whether or not
898  // condensation is a possibility between material layers.
899  Array1D<Real64> CTFTUserOut; // Outside terms of the CTF equation for interior temp
900  // calc@user location
901  Array1D<Real64> CTFTUserIn; // Inside terms of the CTF equation for interior temp
902  // calc@user location
903  Array1D<Real64> CTFTUserSource; // Source/sink terms of the CTF equation for interior temp
904  // calc@user location
905  int NumHistories; // CTFTimeStep/TimeStepZone or the number of temp/flux history series
906  // for the construction
907  int NumCTFTerms; // Number of CTF terms for this construction (not including terms at current time)
908  Real64 UValue; // Overall heat transfer coefficient for the construction
909  int SolutionDimensions; // Number of dimensions in the solution (1 for normal constructions,
910  // 1 or 2 for constructions with sources or sinks)-->may allow 3-D later?
911  int SourceAfterLayer; // Source/sink is present after this layer in the construction
912  int TempAfterLayer; // User is requesting a temperature calculation after this layer in the construction
913  Real64 ThicknessPerpend; // Thickness between planes of symmetry in the direction
914  // perpendicular to the main direction of heat transfer
915  // (same as half the distance between tubes)
916  // Moisture Transfer Functions term belong here as well
917  // BLAST detailed solar model parameters
918  Real64 AbsDiffIn; // Inner absorptance coefficient for diffuse radiation
919  Real64 AbsDiffOut; // Outer absorptance coefficient for diffuse radiation
920  // Variables for window constructions
921  Array1D<Real64> AbsDiff; // Diffuse solar absorptance for each glass layer,
922  // bare glass or shade on
923  Array2D<Real64> BlAbsDiff; // Diffuse solar absorptance for each glass layer vs.
924  // slat angle, blind on
925  Array2D<Real64> BlAbsDiffGnd; // Diffuse ground solar absorptance for each glass layer
926  // vs. slat angle, blind on

928  // vs. slat angle, blind on

930  Array2D<Real64> BlAbsDiffBack; // Diffuse back solar absorptance for each glass layer,
931  // vs. slat angle, blind on
